{"parentUuid": null, "isSidechain": true, "promptId": "6c3a0b22-aa71-4abe-86b8-7ed7f2e35c75", "agentId": "a975ce8c87ff99190", "type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": "Adversarially verify this finding about a design doc (the doc is at /tmp/claude-1000/-home-jleechan-projects-worktree-runner/8ca589dd-8422-44b1-a543-52bd7b71f14b/scratchpad/gistfile1.txt; the repo is /home/jleechan/projects/worktree_runner; you may use WebSearch/WebFetch and read files). Try to REFUTE it. Finding from the \"facts\" reviewer, severity major:\nTITLE: GCE 'no strong KVM' claim is factually wrong \u2014 Compute Engine supports nested virtualization on most Intel x86 machine types\nDETAIL: VERIFIED FALSE: Google Cloud docs (https://docs.cloud.google.com/compute/docs/instances/nested-virtualization/overview) state Compute Engine adds Intel VT-x to VMs so an L1 VM can run KVM. Requirements: Intel Haswell or later CPU platform; enabled per-VM with `--enable-nested-virtualization`; NOT supported on E2, memory-optimized, AMD-based, Arm-based, or H4D machine types. So on a correctly chosen GCE machine type (e.g. N1/N2/C2/C3 Intel), /dev/kvm exists and the design's libvirt backend works \u2014 the backend-selection table row 'Linux / GCE \u2192 No/weak KVM \u2192 Docker+Sysbox' is wrong as a blanket statement. Caveats that partially support the design's instinct: nested KVM has a real performance penalty (see https://piware.de/post/2026-02-13-google-cloud-platform-nested-virtualization-revisited/, Feb 2026), and Arm/AMD GCE instances genuinely have no nested virt. Note the design's own detection code (checking /dev/kvm) would actually pick libvirt on such GCE VMs, contradicting its own table.\nRECOMMENDATION: Change the design text: GCE with Intel machine types + --enable-nested-virtualization is a first-class libvirt/KVM target; Docker+Sysbox is the fallback for E2/AMD/Arm instances or where nested-virt performance is unacceptable. Add a GCE helper that provisions VMs with the nested-virt flag and documents the machine-type constraint.\nIs the finding factually correct and does the recommendation make sense? If the factual basis is wrong or the severity is inflated, refute it. Default to refuted=true only if you have concrete contrary evidence or the claim is unsupported after checking."}, "uuid": "7c2d13a2-5455-4356-8b56-0418f3ae8749", "timestamp": "2026-07-03T22:00:27.965Z", "userType": "external", "entrypoint": "cli", "cwd": "/home/jleechan/projects/worktree_runner", "sessionId": "8ca589dd-8422-44b1-a543-52bd7b71f14b", "version": "2.1.198", "gitBranch": "fix/linux-runner-pre-job-hook", "slug": "velvet-wishing-cake"}
