{"parentUuid": "5f3790a1-dce0-4391-a297-22cc7fe2d78e", "isSidechain": true, "promptId": "6c3a0b22-aa71-4abe-86b8-7ed7f2e35c75", "agentId": "a975ce8c87ff99190", "type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "toolu_01Hp1EWP4puyGM6XE8ZiLMXM", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# Google Compute Engine Nested Virtualization Support\n\nYes, Google Compute Engine supports nested virtualization through Intel VT-x technology, allowing you to run VMs inside other VMs.\n\n## How It Works\n\nThe service adds \"Intel Virtualization Technology (VT-x) instructions to VMs\" so a hypervisor running on a VM can execute additional virtual machines. The setup consists of three levels: L0 (physical host), L1 (VMs on the host), and L2 (VMs inside L1 VMs).\n\n## Requirements & Supported Platforms\n\n- **Hypervisor**: Only Linux KVM is supported; Hyper-V is not supported\n- **Unsupported VM types**: E2 machines, memory-optimized VMs, VMs with AMD/Arm processors, and H4D machines cannot use nested virtualization\n- **Licensed OS**: L2 VMs with licensed operating systems require bring-your-own-license arrangements\n\n## Performance Impact\n\n\"Nested VMs might experience a 10% or greater decrease in performance for workloads that are CPU-bound and possibly greater than a 10% decrease for workloads that are input/output bound.\"\n\n## Implementation Steps\n\n1. Verify the nested virtualization constraint is disabled\n2. Enable nested virtualization on your L1 VM\n3. Create nested L2 VMs within the L1 instance\n\nConsult the referenced guides for detailed configuration instructions and troubleshooting guidance."}]}, "uuid": "577e12df-8aca-4d12-b652-308ee670ea3d", "timestamp": "2026-07-03T22:01:11.412Z", "sourceToolAssistantUUID": "5f3790a1-dce0-4391-a297-22cc7fe2d78e", "userType": "external", "entrypoint": "cli", "cwd": "/home/jleechan/projects/worktree_runner", "sessionId": "8ca589dd-8422-44b1-a543-52bd7b71f14b", "version": "2.1.198", "gitBranch": "fix/linux-runner-pre-job-hook", "slug": "velvet-wishing-cake"}
